w up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gwyn Cywyn ap Gruffudd Lord of Guilsfield was born about 1125, in Guilsfield, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. Gwyn Ap Gruffydd."},"et":{"ABT 1125–":"umbes 1125–Surnud","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1168–Female":"1168–Surnud","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","1125":"1125","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","ABT 1125":"umbes 1125","1130":"1130","about 1168":"umbes 1168","Guilsfield, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Guilsfield, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"ABT 1125–":"noin 1125–Kuollut","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1168–Female":"1168–Kuollut","1125–Male":"1125–Kuollut","1125":"1125","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","ABT 1125":"noin 1125","11